data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and specific assert methods that give **much better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use Assert.AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use Assert.IsTrue with a message for predicate checks
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfied(users, u => u.IsActive); // MSTest v3.x+
    CollectionAssert.Contains(users, users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));

    // Assert.IsNotNull is clearer than Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows `Expected:3 Actual:0` on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent + better message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(predicate)` | `Assert.IsTrue(pred, "msg")` | Without a message you just get `"Expected: True, Actual: False"` |
| manual LINQ checks | `CollectionAssert.*` | Purpose-built: `AllAreSatisfied`, `Contains`, `AreEquivalent`, `IsSubsetOf`, etc. |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `AreEqual` — same elements, same order
- `AreEquivalent` — same elements, any order
- `AllAreSatisfied` — every element matches a predicate (v3+)
- `DoesNotContain` / `IsSubsetOf` — set relationships

If you need even richer fluent assertions, consider adding **FluentAssertions** (`users.Should().OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`), but the built-in APIs cover most cases well.
